##European carmakers have been hit hard by the outbreak, as more than 90 factories shut down

REPORTER: Li Yimeng

So far, the rate of plant shutdowns by mainstream carmakers in Europe may be close to half. The testing of the supply chain has slashed carmakers'expectations of full-year earnings and eroded confidence among local investors.

“

So far, the rate of plant shutdowns by mainstream carmakers in Europe may be close to half. The testing of the supply chain has slashed carmakers'expectations of full-year earnings and eroded confidence among local investors.

”

The new coronavirus epidemic is raging in Europe. The World Health Organization has recently designated Europe as the "Disaster Center" for the new coronavirus pandemic. Several European countries, including Italy, France, the United Kingdom, Germany and Spain, have raised their epidemic prevention levels, and restrictions on movement.

Such campaigns have had a huge impact on European car manufacturing. Car Production Lines in the region have been silent since this week, with more than 90 factories closing.

Volvo cars announced late Tuesday (March 17) that its Ghent plant in Belgium had been shut down since the afternoon. Volvo said the move was aimed at slowing the spread of the new pneumonia among its employees. The government of Belgium recently adopted a series of closure measures in response to the epidemic, resulting in a shortage of staff at the volvogant plant.

The Ghent plant, one of Volvo's four production facilities in Europe, employs about 5,500 people and produces such models as the XC40 and the V60, it also supplies the battery pack for the brand's first fully electric vehicle, the Foshan XC40 Recharge.

Volvo did not give a timetable for the Ghent plant's resumption, but a company insider told interface that the XC40 Recharge, which was due to go on sale overseas in September, was not affected by the suspension. So far, Vîlvă has maintained normal production at the Toslanda assembly plant near Gothenburg, Sweden, as well as at the sjovde powertrain plant and the Olofström body plant.

Volvo is the latest example of a major carmaker shutting down production in Europe.

Earlier in the day, Tuesday Deese, the chairman of VW's Management Board, told the world online that the group's European plants would be temporarily closed.

"faced with a significant drop in sales and uncertainty in the supply chain, our factory has the potential to disrupt production, " Deese said.

Production at the group's factories in Spain and Portugal has been suspended. All production lines in Spain, Portugal, Slovakia and Italy will be suspended until the end of the week. German factories will also be shut down for two to three weeks from Monday.

Volkswagen has 43 production facilities in Europe, covering 17 countries. By country, the current round of temporary closure of up to 24 plants, the proportion of work stoppage close to 56% .

Daimler AG, a German carmaker, made a similar decision on the same day. Tuesday has decided to suspend "most" of its European production and some of its executive branch for an initial two-week period, covering "Daimler's car, truck and commercial vehicle plants in Europe" , the shutdown will begin this week.

In addition to the shutdown, Daimler will also review its global supply chain, which Daimler's current supply chain can not sustain at full capacity. Whether or not the stoppage is extended will depend on the course of events.

Daimler did not disclose the number of affected plants, but from the description in its press release, plant shutdown rate of at least 50% . According to the group's official website, the total number of production facilities in Europe is 16, including outsourcing assembly plants and powertrain plants.

BMW, one of the "German top three" , announced on March 18 that it would close its factories in Europe and South Africa from the weekend until April 19. The manufacturer has 12 production facilities in Europe.

The two French carmakers reacted more quickly. PSA, the parent company of Peugeot, Citroen and others, announced on Monday that it would temporarily close 15 of its European factories until March 27, involving France, Spain, Germany, the United Kingdom, Portugal, Poland, Slovakia and other countries.

The PSA said in a statement, the decision follows "an acceleration of severe COVID-19 cases in recent days near some production sites, supply disruptions at major suppliers and a sudden downturn in the car market" .

PSA has 32 production facilities in Europe, including Russia, with a shutdown rate of 46.9 percent, according to the group's official website.

Following PSA, Renault's Tuesday (17 March) announced it would temporarily close 12 of its plants in France until further information became available, given the spread of the new pneumonia.

Through official channels, Renault said it would stop all production at its French plants in an effort to protect workers. The number of workers affected by the shutdown reached 18,000.

In addition, Reno on Monday (March 16) suspended production at its Baladolid and Valencia plants in Spain because of a shortage of spare parts.

Including brands such as Dacia and Avtovaz  , Reno has 28 production facilities in Europe, including Russia. The total number of plants shut down reached 14, with a shutdown rate of 50% .

In Italy, Europe's worst affected country, Fiat Chrysler Automobiles said Monday that its Italian subsidiary and Maserati's main European plant would suspend production until March 27. The decision was also made in response to a downturn in demand.

FCA group will close six factories in Italy, as well as the KRAGUJEVAC plant in Serbia and the black plant in Poland.

The carmaker operates more than 100 production facilities worldwide, including 23 in Europe, according to its website. FCA's plant shut down rate was 34.8 percent.

Ferrari, the Italian supercar maker that split from FCA in January 2016, also announced on the 14th that its Maranello and Mondner plants in Italy would remain closed until March 27. Because Ferrari only makes cars in Italy, the manufacturer's factory shutdowns are the highest in Europe at 100% .

Nor is the rapid spread of the disease affecting only local carmakers in Europe, with many Asian and US carmakers with capacity deployed in the region also caught up.

Nissan is one example. The Japanese carmaker announced on the 13th that it was suspending production at two factories in Spain. The shutdown will last at least until March 16, a company spokesman said. Nissan employs about 3,000 people at its Spanish plant, which makes models of electric vans and pickup trucks.

On March 18th Nissan added that it had decided to temporarily close its Sandrin plant in the UK after assessing the impact of the current outbreak on the supply chain and market demand.

In Europe, Nissan has a total of four production facilities (including Russia) , the shutdown rate reached 75% .

Toyota, Nissan's domestic rival, announced it would close two plants in France and Portugal from March 18. At the same time, its European headquarters will start telecommuting. Toyota also said its two other plants in the UK and the Czech Republic were not affected.

The Japanese carmaker has six full-vehicle plants in Europe (including Turkey and Russia) and two powertrain plants, according to its website. Toyota's plants in Europe have been shut down at a rate of 25% .

Ford Tuesday, the US carmaker, announced on March 17 that it would suspend production at its Cologne and Sal Louis Plants in Germany, as well as its Craiova plant in Romania. The three plants will be shut down from Thursday (March 19) , with only similar maintenance and security work remaining inside.

Ford's Cologne plant supplies the fiesta and Fox models to the European market, respectively. Although both models have been discontinued in Ford's home market, Florida, they remain the top selling cars in Europe.

Ford had previously closed another vehicle assembly plant in Valencia, Spain, on the 16th, the latter is responsible for the production of wing-tiger models. Over the weekend, three workers at the plant tested positive for the new coronavirus.

Stewart Raleigh, Ford's president for Europe, said the manufacturer had temporarily closed its plants because of problems in its supply chain due to the outbreak. In addition, the safety of employees is also one of its main considerations.

Ford said it may take further action based on a World Health Organization report on the development of the disease in Europe, and did not rule out the possibility of closing more plants.

The US carmaker, which has 13 production facilities in Europe, has a shutdown rate of 30.8 per cent, according to an operational map on its website.

And in Britain, where the epidemic is developing just as rapidly, the country's "herd immunity" response, designed to slow the peak rather than force control, as a result, Britain's industries, including car manufacturing, have not experienced a significant shutdown. The local factories of carmakers such as Jaguar Land Rover, Honda, Toyota and Ford are still operating normally.

In addition, Jaguar Land Rover's five production facilities in Europe have not been shut down.

By rough estimates, the number of European plants suspended by major carmakers could reach 93. On the other hand, including the Jaguar Land Rover, the number of production facilities in the region by major automakers stands at 190, with an overall shutdown rate of 48 percent or more. The proportion is even higher when Russia is excluded.

Supply chain disruption is emerging as the biggest risk to their European operations, in addition to concerns over the health of their workers, in the words of the big carmakers'lockouts.

Michelin, a French tyre supplier, will close factories in Italy, Spain and France from Wednesday (March 18) for a period of "at least a week" .

"Things are getting more complicated and things are changing fast, " Volkswagen said. The group said it had far more European suppliers with capacity in Italy and Spain than its Chinese suppliers.

In addition to having a direct impact on product manufacturing, the epidemic is lowering automakers'expectations for full-year earnings. Pretax profits and new car deliveries could see a big drop in 2020 as a result of the new crown pneumonia epidemic, BMW said on Wednesday as it announced plans to halt work.

Liu Rui, an independent automotive analyst at the University of Engineering and technology in Troyes, France, said that the effects of the new pneumonia on the European car market would persist for the next six to nine months and would be felt even after the outbreak was eliminated.

"given that European countries are just now entering a state of emergency and are beginning to impose restrictions on the movement of people, in the case of China, this phase will last at least three months, " he said, "given the economic environment and health conditions in parts of southern Europe, the impact on the region will be longer, and it is one of the major concentrations of carmakers' production capacity in Europe. "

Deese, chairman of the Volkswagen Group Management Board, made a similar point in an online earnings call on July 17.

"China's response [ to the outbreak ] has been very decisive, ensuring the operation of the supply chain through special security measures. Such measures have been very effective, so the auto industry has recovered quickly, " he said, "If Europe can recover as quickly as China, then a rapid recovery in the market can be expected, but it is not clear how long the impact of the epidemic will last in Europe. "

"With the plant closure, car inventories across Europe will be hit hard. Supply and demand will be hit in the coming weeks, " said Thomas Besson, an analyst at Cheuvreux Kepler.

Jefferies Investment Bank analysts said conditions in the European car market "will deteriorate further" .

The crisis now being experienced by carmakers in Europe has rippled through capital markets. Public concern about the outbreak sent Reno's shares down 20 percent on Monday, while PSA group's shares fell 16 percent.

German carmakers are being tested in the same way. Shares in Daimler, BMW and Volkswagen are down 11 per cent, 12 per cent and 13 per cent respectively so far.
